<br>
To begin with, we were VERY late getting started. This was unavoidable as we had some issues to clear up related to the server reset earlier in the day. To be truthful, I think the long startup time had a direct impact on our discipline the remainder of the night.<br>
<br>
We ended up with a pretty good mix class-wise, though our chronic shortage of healers was once more in evidence. At start time, we had two groups without significant healer support. We kicked the night off with 59 people... well over what I'd actually intended, but doable none the less.<br>
Two groups cleared the spec caves in very short order, and the raid promptly moved into the portal area. A huge thanks to Tremor and Baptismo and all those who helped on the outside. One of the few things that went right was that while we were making the first attempts, the caves were kept cleared for the returning melees.<br>
<br>
We got reorganized in good order, and I briefed the raid again, mostly covering the points I'd already covered, but also explaining the break tactic in more detail. On every important, make-or-break point, I stopped the briefing and had each group leader confirm with each member of their group individually that the point was clear and understood. That turned out to be a total waste of time.<br>
<br>
With the briefing done, the Pull Group sent in a FD watcher to let us know when the portal was clear. Another thing that went right was the Pull Group. Their performance was nothing short of exemplary the entire night.<br>
<br>
With the portal momentarily clear of wanderers, Group 2 zoned in to open the battle. Here is where things started to break down. Group 2 zoned, and made the camp with little difficulty. Group 1 was supposed to follow them in within seconds, but confusion, then a single bad decision on my part left Group 2 fighting alone for far longer than the plan called for. Group 1 finally zoned in, followed in short order by Groups 3 and 4. Within seconds, the camp was trained for the first time on the night. More than one person ran straight out from the portal, down the hill, gathered up a half-dozen mobs, and THEN turned left to find the campsite. Good thing we stopped the briefing to make sure everyone knew how to get to the West camp, I see.<br>
<br>
From here, it was all down hill. Our numbers became rapidly depleted by the failure of some to abide by the instructions on where to bind. Eventually, two full groups from the designated break team had to be replaced because their melees were scattered around Norrath. For the first three charges, we tried to stick with the plan, and even beef it up by adding an extra group. EACH and EVERY charge was marked by MORE THAN ONE person training the camp. Not once or twice were we thwarted by this. SIX times we charged, only to be trained and overwhelmed each time. That is the crux of why were were defeated. I don't care who you are, you will not break Fear if you cannot control the agro to the camp and keep it to a reasonable number of mobs.<br>
<br>
Another thing that went right. Our Enchanters coordinated their efforts, and worked their behinds off trying to keep things at the camp in hand in the face of huge trains. They were thwarted mostly by the sheer number of adds, and on a few occassions by people FAILING TO ASSIST. How basic is this, and how many times did we say it. I do not care if you are standing around wondering what to hit. Under NO circumstances do you EVER manually target and hit auto-attack. A very few people were authorized to do that, while others repeatedly took it on themselves to choose a target.<br>
<br>
Here comes the complaint that &quot;The Main Assist wasn't fighting anything!&quot; or &quot;Assist wasn't working!&quot;. I don't care. You stand there at look at the mobs until the disignated person call their target, even if you fall asleep at the keyboard waiting for it. Now on at least 3 occassions, the complaint actually had some merit. This was because our Druids CHARMED THE PRIMARY TARGET? Okay, this was partially my fault. I suppose most Druids are not used to using this ability in a group situation, and thus are not nearly as adept as the Enchanters are at using it effectively. Still, it seemed pretty obvious to me that you want to charm the ADDS... NOT the primary target! Even with this mistake, however, no one should have taken it on themselves to choose another target until the Main Assist called a new target, and more than one person did just that.<br>
<br>
I'll give each and every one of you credit for having enough heart to sustain this raid as long as it went. For attack after attack, we charged in with enough firepower to take and hold the camp, only to be thwarted by those few who could not hold discipline. You made these charges with minimal whining and bickering, and that speaks well for all of you. You all showed extrodinary patience throughout the night.<br>
<br>
After 6 fruitless charges, and with our force greatly depleted, I called the raid and asked for help in breaking the zone and recovering our bodies. Aeschelus had contacted me shortly after the third charge saying that Forged Alliance could muster the strength for a CR, and that he'd be glad to help if needed. When I asked him after our final charge, he ported over within minutes and began putting the CR team together, filling in the FA teams with our raiders as needed. Many thanks to Forged Alliance, and to those of you who volunteered to charge in yet again. The camp was taken on the first attempt, and was not trained, so was held. Reses began shortly thereafter, with the last being done by about 5 a.m. CST.<br>
<br>
Here are the basic lessons learned:<br>
<br>
1. My plan had a fundamental flaw in that I split our force at the start. This was based on the premise that we would take the camp with a small, disciplined team, then bring in the other teams when the way was clear. I should have used our numbers and taken the whole force in from the first charge on.<br>
<br>
2. The West camp, or any other camp, cannot be broken if people insist on training it. The FD's were reporting to me each time that this person came in with three on them, and that person ran to the camp with 4 on them. If you trained the camp, you know who you are.<br>
<br>
3. Druids, do not charm the primary target. Charm the adds. If you charm the primary target, you throw the force into confusion and discipline evaporates within seconds.<br>
<br>
4. Setting up and using a Pull Group is a viable and effective tactic if you have the right people for it. This group was keeping me aware of the status of the zone right from the beginning, though I didn't always make the best use of their information. If we'd broken the camp, they were organized and ready to begin pulling the zone just as soon as we had everyone in and ready. Sadly, they never had the chance to show off all the preliminary work they did toward that.<br>
<br>
5. Group Sex was the most fun group to be in. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
We were defeated last night, in detail, but if we learn the lessons listed above, and any others that may be added to this thread by the rest of you, we can avoid ever having another disaster of this magnitude. We will be back. This zone, even beefed up, is no match for us if we maintain discipline and do the things we know how to do. Last night, we didn't.<br>
<br>
I apologize wholeheartedly to all of you. The final lesson learned is that I should have come down harder from the first on those people who trained the camp. It's not a lesson I'll forget.<br>
<br>
Many thanks once more to Aeschelus and all those who stopped what they were doing to come over and help us get out of the zone. You have our gratitude, and our congratulations on a job well done.<br>
<br>
